Some final remarks are in order. 
Could a BRST symmetry be found for ordinary second order
theories? Covariance requires that the operator  be at least
quadratic in the derivatives. However, in lower dimensions, this
requirement can be relaxed. Chiral bosons in two dimensions have a
BRST symmetry which allows the vacuum as the only physical state
. In higher dimensions we could consider the
action () without the term  and  as a function
of  and its derivatives. Then we can take 
. The term  in () yields the 
Lagrangian for the ordinary scalar field but we get non-local
interactions with the ghosts due to the term 
. Even though there is a BRST symmetry, a detailed analysis shows
that on-shell  so that the quartet 
mechanism can not be applied. It is imperative to have non-trivial
solutions to the field equation for the quartet mechanism to
work. Since  all 
contributions from the ghost sector to the physical Hilbert space
vanish because they must be functions of . Then we end up with
the usual scalar theory and the BRST symmetry is trivial in this case.

A more radical possibility would be to consider non-local expression
for , for instance 
. The action () with  would be the ordinary one for a
scalar field but for the ghosts we find a non-local
action. Quantization of such non-local theories has been done 
 but it not clear how the quartet mechanism can be
applied with non-local ghosts. This deserves further understanding. 

Returning to the quantum mechanical case, 
the action () resembles that of supersymmetric quantum
mechanics if  and the ghosts are regarded as fermions. The 
BRST transformations () are identical to the supersymmetry
transformations but the anti-BRST transformation (obtained by
replacing ghosts by anti-ghosts and vice-versa) 

 are not. The anti-commutator
of the BRST and anti-BRST transformations 
vanishes as expected while in the supersymmetric case it would be
proportional to the Hamiltonian. There are crucial signs in the action
and in the transformation rules which, when changed, produces the
supersymmetric model. Hence the supersymmetric model is obtained by
twisting the BRST symmetry. 

We should also remark that the BRST symmetry can not be found
in any HD theory. For instance, in the simple case of non-degenerated
masses 
